This paper deals with predicting attention in videos using deep learning-based approaches, which is a popular topic in computer vision. The paper specifically focuses on differentiating between fixations and smooth pursuit eye movements, which are unique to perception of dynamic scenes. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper involves training and evaluating neural networks, which suggests that it may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also involves human-computer interaction, as it deals with predicting attention in human observers, which suggests that it may belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with naturalistic videos, which suggests that it may also belong to the Multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
